Beast DSL Addendum

Temporal Sequences, Hidden Hashes, and Artifact History

Version: Draft
Applies to: Beast2 DSL → Beast3: Starfleet OS

⸻

1. Temporal Sequence Primitive

The Beast DSL now includes a native temporal sequence primitive using the -> operator.

The operator represents ordered time progression between states or actions.

This primitive is designed to be simple enough for voice commands, human reading, and LLM interpretation.

⸻

Syntax

$animation sequence
walk 2s -> run 2m 5s


⸻

Semantics

The -> operator expresses:

state_A(duration) → state_B(duration)

Meaning:
	1.	execute state_A
	2.	after specified duration, transition to state_B

Durations may be expressed in human-readable format:

s   seconds
m   minutes
h   hours

Examples:

walk 2s -> run 5s
idle 10s -> turn_left 1s -> walk 4s


⸻

Design Goals

The sequence primitive prioritizes:
	•	human readability
	•	voice command compatibility
	•	minimal syntax complexity
	•	predictable parsing

Internally this compiles to a deterministic sequence graph.

⸻

2. Hidden Artifact Hashes

Beast artifact identifiers are cryptographic hashes generated automatically.

However:

Hash values are hidden from both humans and LLM interfaces by default.

This reduces cognitive noise and prevents accidental coupling to internal identifiers.

Hashes remain accessible through explicit commands when needed.

⸻

Default CLI Behavior

query artifact history

Example output:

# query results (last 2 revisions)

date: 2004-10-05
1: original gold master
[ block ]

date: 2004-10-06
2: b3_gold_master
[ block ]


⸻

Explicit Hash Retrieval

Hashes may be revealed with an explicit request.

Example:

query artifact history --show-hash

Output:

date: 2004-10-05
hash: a7f91c2d...
1: original gold master

date: 2004-10-06
hash: b83c11ae...
2: b3_gold_master


